    <abstract-text>During the last decade, the molecular mechanisms of plant growth and development
        have been studied in detail. The role of the plant-specific family of GRAS-proteins in these
        processes has become apparent. In this study, the importance of DELLA-proteins has been
        highlighted and a model of gibberellin-signaling pathways in plants has been shown. The
        starting point of this model is binding of biologically active gibberellic acid to a
        receptor and DELLA-protein. Such complex ubiquitinates and becomes a target for proteasomal
        degradation. The degradation of DELLA-proteins leads to the derepression of plant growth and
        to a gibberellin response, which is manifested by the induction of growth processes. The
        molecular functioning mechanisms of DELLA-proteins as transcription factors are
        discussed.</abstract-text>
